The '''Free Speech Movement''' ('''FSM''') was a massive, long-lasting [[student protest]] which took place during the 1964–65 academic year on the campus of the [[University of California, Berkeley]].<ref>'''Sources''':
*{{Cite web|url=http://fsm.berkeley.edu/|title=Berkeley FSM {{!}} Free Speech Movement 50th Anniversary|website=fsm.berkeley.edu|ref=":0"|access-date=2017-08-18}}
*{{Cite web|url=https://calisphere.org/exhibitions/43/the-free-speech-movement/|title=The Free Speech Movement|website=Calisphere|language=en|access-date=2017-08-18}}
*{{Cite web|url=http://www.fsm-a.org/|title=Free Speech Movement Archives|website=www.fsm-a.org|access-date=2017-08-18}}
*{{Cite web|url=http://bancroft.berkeley.edu/CalHistory/60s.html|title=Days of Cal {{!}} Berkeley in the 60s|website=bancroft.berkeley.edu|access-date=2017-08-18}}
*{{Cite web|url=http://picturethis.museumca.org/timeline/unforgettable-change-1960s/free-speech-movement/info|title=Unforgettable Change: 1960s: Free Speech Movement & The New American Left {{!}} Picture This|website=picturethis.museumca.org|language=en|access-date=2017-08-18}}</ref> The Movement was informally under the central leadership of Berkeley graduate student [[Mario Savio]].<ref>'''Sources''':
*{{Cite web|url=http://fsm.berkeley.edu/|title=Berkeley FSM {{!}} Free Speech Movement 50th Anniversary|website=fsm.berkeley.edu|language=en-US|access-date=2017-08-18}}
*{{Cite web|url=https://calisphere.org/exhibitions/43/the-free-speech-movement/|title=The Free Speech Movement|website=Calisphere|language=en|access-date=2017-08-18}}
*{{Cite web|url=http://www.savio.org/who_was_mario.html|title=Who Was Mario? :: Mario Savio Memorial Lecture Fund|website=www.savio.org|access-date=2017-08-18}}</ref> Other student leaders include [[Jack Weinberg]], Michael Rossman, George Barton, Brian Turner, [[Bettina Aptheker]], Steve Weissman, Michael Teal, Art Goldberg, [[Jackie Goldberg]], and others.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fsm.berkeley.edu/notable-bios/|title=Notable Bios {{!}} Berkeley FSM|website=fsm.berkeley.edu|language=en-US|access-date=2017-08-18}}</ref>

With the participation of thousands of students, the Free Speech Movement was the first mass act of civil disobedience on an American college campus in the 1960s.<ref>'''Sources''':
*{{Cite web|url=http://fsm.berkeley.edu/|title=Berkeley FSM {{!}} Free Speech Movement 50th Anniversary|website=fsm.berkeley.edu|access-date=2017-08-18}}
*{{Cite web|url=http://bancroft.berkeley.edu/CalHistory/60s.html|title=Days of Cal {{!}} Berkeley in the 60s|website=bancroft.berkeley.edu|access-date=2017-08-18}}
*{{Cite web|url=http://picturethis.museumca.org/timeline/unforgettable-change-1960s/free-speech-movement/info|title=Unforgettable Change: 1960s: Free Speech Movement & The New American Left {{!}} Picture This|website=picturethis.museumca.org|language=en|access-date=2017-08-18}}
*{{Cite web|url=http://fsm.berkeley.edu/free-speech-movement-timeline/|title=Visual History: Free Speech Movement, 1964 {{!}} Berkeley FSM|website=fsm.berkeley.edu|language=en-US|access-date=2017-08-18}}</ref> Students insisted that the university administration lift the ban of on-campus political activities and acknowledge the students' right to [[free speech]] and [[academic freedom]]. The Free Speech Movement was influenced by the [[New Left]],<ref name="cityjournal">{{cite web |last1=Stern |first1=Sol |title=The Free Speech Movement at 50 |url=https://www.city-journal.org/html/free-speech-movement-50-11433.html |publisher=''City Journal'' |date=September 25, 2014}}</ref> and was also related to the [[Civil Rights Movement]] and the [[Opposition to United States involvement in the Vietnam War|Anti-Vietnam War Movement]].<ref>'''Sources''':
